        <title>Layer object</title>
        <paragraph><literal>app.project.item(index).layer(index)</literal></paragraph>
        <paragraph><strong>Description</strong></paragraph>
        <paragraph>The Layer object provides access to layers within compositions. It can be accessed from an item’s layer collection either by index number or by a name string.</paragraph>
        <block_quote>
            <paragraph>Layer is a subclass of <reference internal="True" refuri="../properties/propertygroup#propertygroup"><inline classes="std std-ref">PropertyGroup</inline></reference>, which is a subclass of <reference internal="True" refuri="../properties/propertybase#propertybase"><inline classes="std std-ref">PropertyBase</inline></reference>. All methods and attributes of PropertyGroup, in addition to those listed below, are available when working with Layer, with the exception that <literal>propertyIndex</literal> attribute is set to <literal>undefined</literal>.</paragraph>
            <paragraph>Layer is the base class for <reference internal="True" refuri="cameralayer#cameralayer"><inline classes="std std-ref">CameraLayer object</inline></reference>, <reference internal="True" refuri="lightlayer#lightlayer"><inline classes="std std-ref">LightLayer object</inline></reference>, and <reference internal="True" refuri="avlayer#avlayer"><inline classes="std std-ref">AVLayer object</inline></reference>, so Layer attributes and methods are available when working with all layer types. Layers contain AE properties, in addition to their JavaScript attributes and methods. For examples of how to access properties in layers, see <reference internal="True" refuri="../properties/propertybase#propertybase"><inline classes="std std-ref">PropertyBase object</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
        </block_quote>
        <paragraph><strong>Example</strong></paragraph>
        <paragraph>If the first item in the project is a <reference internal="True" refuri="../items/compitem#compitem"><inline classes="std std-ref">CompItem</inline></reference>, this example disables the first layer in that composition and renames it. This might, for example, turn an icon off in the composition.</paragraph>
        <literal_block classes="code javascript" force_highlighting="False" language="javascript" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve"><inline classes="keyword declaration">var</inline> <inline classes="name other">firstLayer</inline> <inline classes="operator">=</inline> <inline classes="name other">app</inline><inline classes="punctuation">.</inline><inline classes="name other">project</inline><inline classes="punctuation">.</inline><inline classes="name other">item</inline><inline classes="punctuation">(</inline><inline classes="literal number integer">1</inline><inline classes="punctuation">).</inline><inline classes="name other">layer</inline><inline classes="punctuation">(</inline><inline classes="literal number integer">1</inline><inline classes="punctuation">);</inline>
<inline classes="name other">firstLayer</inline><inline classes="punctuation">.</inline><inline classes="name other">enabled</inline> <inline classes="operator">=</inline> <inline classes="keyword constant">false</inline><inline classes="punctuation">;</inline>
<inline classes="name other">firstLayer</inline><inline classes="punctuation">.</inline><inline classes="name other">name</inline> <inline classes="operator">=</inline> <inline classes="literal string double">"DisabledLayer"</inline><inline classes="punctuation">;</inline></literal_block>
